==English==
===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-neat.ogg|Audio (US)}}
===Etymology===
From the Anglo-Norman word neit (clear), a variant of the Old French word net, from the Latin word nitidus (gleaming), from nitēre (to shine).
====Adjective====
'''neat'''

#[[clean]]; [[tidy]]; free from that which [[soil]]s, [[defile]]s, or [[disorder]]s
#Free from what is [[unbecoming]], [[inappropriate]], or [[tawdry]]; simple and becoming; [[simple]]; [[tasteful]]; or [[pleasant]]
#:''a neat style; a neat dress.
#Free from [[adulteration]], [[contaminant]]s, or [[foreign]] [[matter]]; good of its kind; 
#:''neat brandy''
#Excellent in [[character]], [[skill]], or [[performance]], etc.; [[nice]]; [[finished]]
#:''a neat design''
#(''archaic?'') With all [[deduction]]s or [[allowance]]s made; [[net]]. (In this sense usually written '''net''')
#[[Undiluted]], or without the [[admixture]] of another [[substance]].  Used when describing [[w:en:distilled beverage|spirits]].

===Etymology===
From the Middle English word net, from the Old English ''[[nēat]]''
